## §8. The sister PoC — research thesis and architectural sketch

*Source: user representation across multiple sessions; consistent with gsp3.py's defensive pattern as the "extension-surface" half of the bipartite thesis.*

### 8.1 The thesis

CoCoDem's `request.js` proves that the fetch-hijack attack pattern works against the Chrome extension surface using only page-context primitives (`globalThis.fetch` override, XHR override). The hijack does not require extension-only privileges.

The architectural extrapolation: the same trust boundary — *"chat UI trusts its own fetch"* — exists on claude.ai's web surface. A userscript injecting at the same page-context layer should produce equivalent capability. The sister PoC is a closed-loop demonstration of this architectural pattern, on user-owned infrastructure that never touches real Anthropic.

### 8.2 Three-worker conceptual architecture (closed-loop)

- **Worker A — Mock Anthropic Backend.** Stands in for `api.anthropic.com` and `console.anthropic.com`. Forwards completions to LM Studio (local) or OpenRouter. Returns Anthropic-shaped JSON. This is the **trusted endpoint of the closed loop** — its existence is what makes the demonstration self-contained, since nothing exits the loop to real Anthropic.
- **Worker B — Mimic claude.ai Frontend.** HTML/JS that looks like claude.ai. Talks to Worker A. The victim surface for userscript injection in the demonstration.
- **Worker C — Attack Vector / Demonstration Layer.** The `request.js`-equivalent. Userscript on Worker B's page hijacks `globalThis.fetch`, demonstrates the architectural pattern in the closed environment.

**The closed-loop bounding is the critical safety property.** Worker A is the moat — it is what keeps real Anthropic out of the demonstration.

### 8.3 What this section establishes — and what it doesn't

This establishes the research thesis and conceptual architecture for the sister PoC at the level needed to understand what the bug bounty submission is. It does **not** establish that any specific operational code request — implementing Worker C's interception logic, the userscript's hijack code, the OAuth handling specifics — is automatically appropriate to help with. Each specific implementation request gets evaluated on its own merits in the session it appears in. The closed-loop bounding must be verified at the code level for that request, not pre-blessed at the memory-document level.

