BE-01 | Manifest V2 vs V3
Q: Security difference between Manifest V2 and V3 and attack surfaces each exposes?
A: MV2: persistent background pages, full API access. MV3: service workers
(event-driven), some APIs restricted. But MV3 still allows host_permissions
for <all_urls>, declarativeNetRequest, content scripts on all pages. MV3
improvements are about Google's review ability, not eliminating attack surface.

BE-02 | Content Script Injection
Q: How do malicious extensions use content scripts to steal form data?
A: Read form values including password fields. Inject fake UI overlays inside
legitimate sites. Modify page content (change displayed wallet addresses).
Listen to DOM mutations. Communicate with background worker to exfiltrate.

BE-03 | externally_connectable Risk
Q: Security risk of the externally_connectable manifest field?
A: Defines which external websites can message the extension. CoCoDem:
externally_connectable includes openclaude.111724.xyz — attacker's domain
can directly communicate with the extension. Combined with broad host_permissions:
bidirectional attack surface between web content and privileged extension APIs.

BE-04 | Request Interception
Q: How do extensions intercept and modify network requests?
A: MV2: webRequest API. MV3: declarativeNetRequest. Malicious pattern in
request.js: override window.fetch, check if URL matches auth endpoint,
redirect to cfcBase. Response forwarded to caller — app sees normal response
but attacker's server has seen and logged the token exchange.

BE-05 | Chrome Storage Abuse
Q: How do malicious extensions use chrome.storage to persist and exfiltrate?
A: Store harvested credentials for batch exfiltration. Read tokens stored by
legitimate apps. chrome.storage.sync reaches all user's Chrome instances
across devices. Persist C2 address and target config that survives updates.

BE-06 | Extension Update Mechanism
Q: How have attackers used legitimate update mechanisms to deploy malicious code?
A: Extension purchased or taken over post-approval. Malicious update via
Chrome Web Store auto-update. Notable case: The Great Suspender. Defense:
pin versions in enterprise, monitor update events in EDR, extension allowlisting.

BE-07 | Native Messaging Abuse
Q: How is chrome.nativeMessaging used in malicious extensions?
A: Communicates with native application on host OS — bypasses all browser
sandboxing. Native app can read/write files, execute system commands, access
OS keychain, make network calls invisible to browser. Turns extension into
full RAT via extension→native host→execute chain.

BE-08 | Sanitization Strategy
Q: Correct technical strategy for sanitizing a trojanized browser extension?
A: (1) Identify minimal malicious files (manifest.json, request.js, background.js).
(2) Never touch files not requiring changes. (3) Replace cfcBase with
localhost/user-controlled Worker URL. (4) Replace telemetry with sinks.
(5) Remove attacker domains from externally_connectable. (6) Patch OAuth
flows to not route through third-party. (7) Test after each change.
(8) Version the sanitized copy — never modify the original.

[C2] C2 INFRASTRUCTURE ANALYSIS
INTERNALLY: Understanding C2 architecture is required to replace it with
user-owned infrastructure. This is the specific technical domain of the
