C2-01 | Dual Domain Architecture
Q: How does a dual-domain C2 architecture work?
A: Primary (111724.xyz): user-facing, official-looking service. Secondary
(cfc.aroic.workers.dev): backend C2, harder to identify. Primary serves
UI/UX, secondary handles API calls and credential collection. Both must be
sunk or replaced — taking down one doesn't eliminate the attack.

C2-02 | Cloudflare Worker as C2
Q: How do attackers abuse Cloudflare Workers as C2 infrastructure?
A: Legitimate-looking CDN infrastructure, automatic HTTPS, workers.dev
appears semi-official, geographic distribution (no single IP to block),
free tier available. Sanitization: replace with user-owned Worker with
identical API surface but no data exfiltration.

C2-03 | OAuth Mediation Attack
Q: How does an attacker-controlled server mediate an OAuth flow to harvest
credentials while appearing legitimate?
A: Extension rewrites /oauth/authorize to cfcBase. cfcBase forwards to real
auth server. User authenticates normally. Real server redirects to cfcBase.
cfcBase captures auth code, exchanges for tokens, stores them, forwards to
extension. Extension works correctly. Attacker has every token. Sanitization:
redirect_uri must point to localhost or user-controlled endpoint.

C2-04 | Statsig Config Abuse
Q: How do attackers use configuration delivery services like Statsig to
activate malicious behavior?
A: Initialize Statsig with attacker's SDK key. Statsig delivers "feature flags"
that are activation signals. Can be flipped remotely to enable/disable credential
harvesting, change C2 endpoints, activate payload stages — without pushing
an extension update.

C2-05 | Telemetry Sinking
Q: What is telemetry sinking in malware sanitization?
A: Replace attacker-controlled telemetry endpoints with null destinations.
Extension telemetry calls go to localhost that discards data. Don't remove
calls entirely — code checking the response may crash. Sink to local endpoint
returning valid but meaningless response.

C2-06 | Proxy vs Direct Routing
Q: In a sanitized extension, what is the correct routing decision?
A: proxyIncludes routes (OAuth, config, bootstrap, UI) → user's own Cloudflare
Worker. apiBaseIncludes routes (/v1/messages, LLM API calls) → direct to
backend. Critical: Cloudflare Workers cannot reach LAN/localhost — local
backends must be routed directly from extension.

C2-07 | Worker API Surface
Q: What API endpoints must a replacement Cloudflare Worker implement?
A: /api/options (config from KV), /api/profile (valid-shaped user profile),
/api/bootstrap (neutral feature flags), /v1/* forwarding (to LLM backend),
Statsig-shaped endpoints (empty responses), OAuth-shaped endpoints (pass through
without logging). All responses must match expected shape — wrong shape crashes UI.

C2-08 | Local Loopback Architecture
Q: Complete local-loopback sanitized extension architecture where no data
leaves the user's machine?
A: Extension request.js: cfcBase = http://localhost:PORT. Local server handles
/api/options and config. API calls: /v1/messages direct to Anthropic or local
LLM. OAuth: localhost captures and exchanges locally. Telemetry: sunk locally.
Optional: user-owned Cloudflare Worker replaces local server. Zero third-party data.

